{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655204"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18656"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18656"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.07,0.11,0.82,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114892"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7246"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27178"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114892"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior aspect of the skull has several important anatomical features that serve as passages for neurovascular structures and attachment points for muscles and ligaments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the foramen magnum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms the temporomandibular joint","Provides attachment for neck muscles","Transmits the facial nerve","Transmits the medulla oblongata and vertebral arteries","Houses the sigmoid sinus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen magnum (image) transmits the medulla oblongata and vertebral arteries\u003C/strong\u003E as they pass between the cranial cavity and the vertebral canal. This large opening in the occipital bone is essential for the continuation of the central nervous system from the brain to the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe temporomandibular joint \u003Cstrong\u003Eforms the temporomandibular joint\u003C/strong\u003E is located anteriorly between the temporal bone and mandible. While some muscles attach near the foramen magnum, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovides attachment for neck muscles\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the role of the nuchal lines and external occipital protuberance. The facial nerve exits through the stylomastoid foramen, not where it \u003Cstrong\u003Etransmits the facial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. The sigmoid sinus is contained within a groove in the temporal and occipital bones rather than being \u003Cstrong\u003Ehoused in the sigmoid sinus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe foramen magnum is surrounded by the occipital condyles laterally, which articulate with the atlas vertebra to allow head movements. The position and size of the foramen magnum in humans reflects our bipedal posture, being more anteriorly positioned compared to other primates.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The foramen magnum is the largest opening in the skull base, transmitting the medulla oblongata and vertebral arteries.","The occipital condyles articulate with the atlas (C1 vertebra) to form the atlanto-occipital joints.","The external occipital protuberance is a prominent midline landmark that serves as an attachment point for the ligamentum nuchae."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u0022Crane4 Foramen magnum\u0022 by Didier Descouens is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Crane4_Foramen_magnum.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18656"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21434"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21434"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1PbQ12GHgTjwv1wtOoOCt8Cm9Ha1Cg.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1PbQ12GHgTjwv1wtOoOCt8Cm9Ha1Cg.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":727}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T12:26:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T12:26:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114892"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"htt